---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
---

<Base title="Why I Chose a Static-First Architecture">
  <Header />
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 font-mono">
    <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground mb-8 inline-block">← back to blog</a>

    <header class="mb-8">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-normal mb-2">Why I Chose a Static-First Architecture</h1>
      <time class="text-xs text-muted-foreground" datetime="2025-11-05">November 5, 2025</time>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>When rebuilding my personal site, I made a controversial choice: <strong>ditch the database entirely</strong>.</p>

      <h2>The Problem</h2>
      <p>My original architecture had every page load triggering a database query. For a personal site with mostly static content, this was overkill.</p>
      <p><strong>The costs:</strong> $25/month for database hosting, 100-200ms query latency on every page load, complex deployment, and potential security vulnerabilities.</p>

      <h2>The Solution</h2>
      <p>I moved to a <strong>static-first architecture</strong>: content files get transformed at build time into optimized output, served from a CDN.</p>
      <p><strong>The benefits:</strong> $0/month hosting, 10-20ms load time, dead simple deployment (just push to Git), and zero security surface area.</p>

      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <h3>1. Content Lives in Markdown/YAML</h3>
      <p>Instead of a database, blog posts are markdown files with frontmatter. Much nicer than a textarea in an admin UI.</p>

      <h3>2. Build Script Transforms Content</h3>
      <p>At build time, a script reads all markdown files and generates optimized output. Runs in 0.01 seconds for the entire site.</p>

      <h3>3. Frontend Serves Static Assets</h3>
      <p>Components load pre-generated data. Cached by the CDN, loads <strong>instantly</strong>.</p>

      <h2>The Results</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Metric</th><th>Before</th><th>After</th><th>Improvement</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Load Time</td><td>200ms</td><td>20ms</td><td><strong>10x faster</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hosting Cost</td><td>$25/mo</td><td>$0/mo</td><td><strong>100% savings</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Complex</td><td>git push</td><td><strong>Effortless</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>When NOT to Use Static-First</h2>
      <p><strong>Don't use it if:</strong> you need real-time data, user-generated content, frequently changing content, or complex queries.</p>
      <p><strong>Do use it if:</strong> your content is mostly static, you value performance and simplicity, you want content in version control.</p>

      <h2>The Future</h2>
      <p>Static-first doesn't mean static-only. You can add comments (Giscus), analytics (Plausible), contact forms (serverless functions), and search (Fuse.js). Best of both worlds.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>Moving to static-first was one of the best architectural decisions I've made. My site is faster, cheaper, more reliable, and easier to maintain.</p>
      <p>If your content is mostly static, <strong>question whether you really need that database</strong>.</p>

      <hr />
      <p><em>This post was written in Vim, committed to Git, and published in 30 seconds. No admin UI required.</em></p>
    </div>

    <footer class="mt-12 border-t border-border pt-8">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground">← back to all posts</a>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Base>
